ravelogue, interviewing several of them eyetoeye. The many counts and barons among his 1934 contacts are a proof of Leigh Fermor's lifelong attraction to the aristocracy. Rich with photos and other documents on places and persons both from the thirties and today, the book offers a compelling social and political history of the period and the area. It provides a particular portrait of Hungary and Transylvania when they were on the brink of momentous change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aTravel / Essays & Travelogues.2bisacsh  a20th century, Aristocracy, Constantinople, Hungary, Transylvania, Travel writing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2018z978311078052940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633861721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633861721/original  a978-3-11-078052-9  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK